    "constituents_description": "The most important healing constituents of Epacris tasmanica are quercetin, flavonoids, kaempferol, epicatechin, and phenolic acids, which have been identified through various studies. Quercetin and kaempferol are potent antioxidants with anti-inflammatory properties, attributed to their ability to scavenge free radicals and inhibit the production of pro-inflammatory enzymes. Flavonoids, a subclass of phenolic compounds, have been shown to possess anti-cancer and anti-diabetic properties, as well as to modulate the immune system. Epicatechin, a flavan-3-ol, has been found to have vasodilatory effects, improving cardiovascular health by enhancing blood flow and reducing blood pressure. Phenolic acids, such as those present in Epacris tasmanica, have been demonstrated to exhibit antimicrobial and anti-inflammatory activities, making them valuable for wound healing and tissue repair.",
