    "preparations_description": "The main herbal preparations of Epacris tasmanica are derived from its leaves and flowers, which are rich in flavonoids, phenolic acids, and essential oils. A tea is made by infusing the leaves and flowers in boiling water to produce a potentially antimicrobial and anti-inflammatory brew. A tincture is prepared by macerating the leaves and flowers in a solvent like ethanol or glycerin to create a concentrated liquid extract with possible antiseptic and analgesic properties. An infusion or cold water extract is used to make a salve or topical cream, where the leaves and flowers are infused in a carrier oil like coconut or olive oil to produce an infused oil, which may be used to soothe skin irritations. These preparations have not been extensively studied, but their potential benefits may be attributed to the plant's antioxidant, anti-inflammatory, and antimicrobial properties.",
